WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
6.0 English

2
00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:05.000
From BBCLearningEnglish.com

3
00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:11.000
Hello, this is 6 Minute English from BBCLearningEnglish.

4
00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:13.000
I'm Neil and I'm Beth.

5
00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:25.000
Nowadays, it's popular to find out more about your family history by tracing your family tree, a diagram that shows all the members of a family over a long period of time.

6
00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:28.000
What do you know about your family history, Beth?

7
00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:37.000
Well, my mum actually did our family tree. She found a lot of ancestors had emigrated to the United States.

8
00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:41.000
But yeah, I don't know much more than that. What about you?

9
00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:48.000
Well, I'm lucky to have an unusual surname, so it's quite easy to trace my ancestors.

10
00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:55.000
And somebody in my family has gone back to 1700 and found somebody with my name.

11
00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:05.000
Wow, that's amazing. Well, the internet has made it easier to find the historical records needed to research your ancestry, the origins of your family.

12
00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:10.000
But what if you want to find out about a time before historical records began?

13
00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:15.000
Luckily, some companies now offer to trace your ancestry using DNA.

14
00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:23.000
DNA is the cellular information that's passed down from parents to children, telling the body how to create life.

15
00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:31.000
It's no Chris from the UK recently took a DNA ancestry test when the test returns some unexpected results.

16
00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:37.000
Chris called BBC Radio 4 program, sliced bread, wondering how accurate they really were.

17
00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:43.000
Not so long ago, I sent off a home DNA testing kit.

18
00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:51.000
And the results that came back were broadly in line with expectations, but it had some little glitches in there, which made me think,

19
00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:55.000
is this accurate or is it to be taken with a pinch of salt?

20
00:01:55.000 --> 00:02:04.000
Chris wondered whether his results were accurate or whether to take them with a pinch of salt, an idea meaning to doubt something is completely true.

21
00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:14.000
So, in this program, we'll discuss how accurate DNA ancestry tracing is, and as usual, we'll learn some useful new words and phrases.

22
00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:20.000
And remember, you can find all the vocabulary for this program on our website, BBCLearningEnglish.com.

23
00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:23.000
First though, I have a question for you, Beth.

24
00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:30.000
One reason that to be cautious about DNA ancestry tests is that humans are very similar to each other.

25
00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:41.000
Most of your DNA is identical with every other person on earth, and it's only the tiny amount of difference that accounts for all genetic variations between humans.

26
00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:47.000
So, exactly how much DNA dehumans share with each other.

27
00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:56.000
Is it a 79.9%, b 89.9%, or c 99.9%.

28
00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:59.000
I am going to guess 99.9%.

29
00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:03.000
Okay, well, we'll find out the answer later in the program.

30
00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:11.000
Another problem for research based on DNA is agreeing on the meaning of words like ancestry and ethnicity.

31
00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:19.000
Here, genealogist Louise Bulldog explains the difference between these words to BBC Radio 4 program, sliced bread.

32
00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:24.000
So, ancestry is really about people. It's about your actual forebest.

33
00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:33.000
Your ethnicity, we would probably think of in geographical terms, maybe which continent or which region your people came from.

34
00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:40.000
Like ancestors, the term forebest means actual people, the relatives in your family from a long time ago.

35
00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:52.000
But Louise is more interested in the term ethnicity, the shared culture, language and traditions of a group of people, and this is closely connected to a geographical location.

36
00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:57.000
And it's this question of geography, which interested BBC presenter Greg Foot.

37
00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:05.000
Greg sent DNA samples to two different companies. The results from the first company matched what he already knew about his family,

38
00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:08.000
that the past five generations came from England.

39
00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:17.000
But listen to what happens when Louise Bulldog revealed the results of Greg's second DNA test on his BBC Radio 4 show, sliced bread.

40
00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:19.000
It's going to play your mind.

41
00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:23.000
Can I tell you what you're looking at? Yes, please do.

42
00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:32.000
It says that you are first of all, 66% north and west Europe, but explicitly that doesn't refer to the United Kingdom.

43
00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:35.000
Okay, that's a wide geographical area.

44
00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:42.000
27.5% Irish, gotish and Welsh, but again, explicitly not English.

45
00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:46.000
The second company's DNA test blows Greg's mind.

46
00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:53.000
It makes him very excited and surprised. There's no evidence of his ancestors being English at all.

47
00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:58.000
Actually, companies compared DNA with other samples in their database.

48
00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:04.000
And since companies use different databases, it's not too surprising that Greg's results were so different.

49
00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:06.000
Unlike his actual DNA.

50
00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:10.000
Speaking of which, what was the answer to your question, Neil?

51
00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:16.000
I asked you what percentage of human DNA is shared by everyone?

52
00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:20.000
And what was your answer, Beth? I said 99.9%.

53
00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:24.000
Well, you must be very clever, because the answer is correct.

54
00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:29.000
Well done. Right, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned starting with Family Tree.

55
00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:32.000
A diagram showing all the members of a family.

56
00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:35.000
Ancestry refers to the origins of a family.

57
00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:39.000
If you take something with a pinch of salt, you don't believe it's completely true.

58
00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:43.000
Four bears are relatives who lived in the past.

59
00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:49.000
Ethnicity means the social, cultural and linguistic characteristics shared by a group of people.

60
00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:54.000
And finally, if something blows your mind, it makes you excited or surprised.

61
00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:56.000
Once again, our six minutes are up.

62
00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:00.000
But why not head over to the BBC Learning English website,

63
00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:04.000
where you'll find a worksheet and quiz, especially for this programme.

64
00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:05.000
See you there soon.

65
00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:06.000
Goodbye.
